  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of disguising the origin of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. Key legal definitions typically include:\n\n1. Basic components:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly \"clean\" money\n- Making illegal funds appear legally acquired\n\n2. Legal stages usually include:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (concealing money's origin through complex transactions)\n- Integration (withdrawing transformed money into legitimate economy)\n\n3. Specific criminal statutes vary by jurisdiction, but generally involve:\n- Intentional financial transactions to hide criminal proceeds\n- Knowingly engaging in transactions with illegal source funds\n- Attempting to disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of illegal assets\n\n4. Typical predicate crimes include:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Illegal arms sales\n- Terrorist financing\n\n5. Most jurisdictions require proving:\n- Existence of underlying criminal activity\n- Intent to conceal illegal funds\n- Knowledge of funds' criminal origin\n\nSpecific legal definitions can vary significantly between countries and legal systems.",
